  "opinion": "As a 62-year-old self-employed carpenter from Lecce, I approach fake content on social media with a mix of caution and practicality, shaped by my life experiences and traits. I spend about an hour daily on social media, mostly to stay connected with my two children and enjoy hobbies like knitting and cinema, but I've seen how misinformation can spread quickly and cause unnecessary worry. My high conscientiousness score of 85 means I value accuracy and responsibility, so I always double-check information before sharing it, especially since my low openness of 17 makes me skeptical of new or sensational claims. Being anxious, with a neuroticism score of 79, I feel a personal duty to avoid contributing to the chaos that fake content can create, as it often preys on fears and emotions. In my work as a carpenter, precision is key—just as I measure twice and cut once to avoid mistakes, I verify sources and look for trusted news outlets or official statements before believing or passing on anything online. My Christian beliefs guide me to act with honesty and integrity, so I refrain from engaging with or spreading content that seems deceitful or harmful. Since I'm widowed and have a low extraversion score of 31, I prefer quiet, reliable interactions over viral trends, and I encourage my family and friends to do the same by discussing what we see and questioning its validity. Managing fake content isn't just about technology; it's about cultivating a mindset of carefulness and community support, drawing on my practical skills and anxious nature to navigate social media safely without letting it overwhelm my daily life.",
